---
import ChapterShell from "../../../components/ChapterShell.astro";
import Section from "../../../components/Section.astro";
import DiagramFigure from "../../../components/diagrams/DiagramFigure.astro";
import SelfCheckKeystone from "../../../components/diagrams/SelfCheckKeystone.astro";
import RepairBudgetFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/RepairBudgetFlow.astro";
import AuthoritySplitFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/AuthoritySplitFlow.astro";
import PlanThenEvidenceFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/PlanThenEvidenceFlow.astro";
---

<ChapterShell chapterId="05" locale="en">
  <div slot="thesis">
    <p>
      An Agent may inspect its own output, but must not write “I think I’m done” as final authority.
      Self-check is a bounded feedback loop: it helps repair; it does not take over facts. Key line:
      <strong>Self-check can produce evidence and feedback; it cannot manufacture trust.</strong>
    </p>
  </div>

  <Section
    id="scene"
    label="§05 · Scene"
    title="Start from “I’ve already checked”"
    lede="Free-form reflection restates intent; unbounded check–fix becomes a second Agent loop without budget."
  >
    <p>
      Suppose after a complex migration the Agent replies “done — the code should work.” It has not
      answered: which final artifacts were checked, which public commands ran, exit codes, whether
      temporary output stayed in scratch, whether the final workspace was polluted, whether new files
      are planned deliverables or accidental side effects, whether evidence came only from public task
      materials, and how many repair rounds failure allows.
    </p>
    <blockquote class="pull">
      How do you give the model a chance to discover its own mistakes while putting self-check inputs,
      evidence, side effects, and retry counts into a protocol the Runtime can inspect?
    </blockquote>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="keystone"
    label="§05 · Keystone"
    title="Self-check is a Feedback Plane, not an Authority Plane"
    lede="Model reports; Runtime admits, audits, and bounds."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      prototype
      caption="Fig. 1 · Plan → Evidence → Source Guard → Semantic gate → bounded repair; the model cannot grant infinite self-proof."
      alt="Five-step feedback plane: Plan, Evidence, Source Guard, Semantic gate, Bounded repair; invariant: Self-check produces evidence and feedback, not trust."
    >
      <SelfCheckKeystone />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Self-check Plan</strong> — what to check and where temporary output goes (model
        submits; Runtime admits)
      </li>
      <li><strong>Public Evidence</strong> — what was actually executed or observed (with source refs)</li>
      <li>
        <strong>Source Guard</strong> — whether only public task materials are cited (deterministic policy)
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Hygiene / Consistency Audit</strong> — whether work left scratch or produced unplanned side effects
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Repair Gate</strong> — whether one extra check/repair Turn is allowed (capped)
      </li>
    </ul>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="plan"
    label="§05 · Plan"
    title="Why a Self-check Plan must come first"
    lede="Checking itself has side effects; post-hoc rationalization cannot distinguish prior intent."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 4 · Plan submit → Runtime admit → Evidence submit → Strong pass?; missing plan can block."
      alt="Four steps: Plan submit, Runtime admit, Evidence submit, Strong pass."
    >
      <PlanThenEvidenceFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <p>
      Compiles may write object files; scripts may overwrite deliverables; “verification output” may
      change the workspace listing. If the Agent only explains “those files were temporary” after the
      check, Runtime cannot tell prior plan from post-hoc story. Hence
      <code>self_check_plan_submit</code> first: declare finalArtifacts, selfCheckScratch,
      workspaceGuardPlan — a stable baseline for later audit. Without a plan, facts may still enter
      Task Events, but a strong pass gate can block with <code>missing_self_check_plan</code> — the
      tool layer may record; the gate layer decides whether semantic completion is supported.
    </p>
    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">Evolution aside</p>
      <p>
        Self-check architecture chapter land:
        <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}history/pr/774`}>maka:pr:774</a>
        (docs: add self-check architecture chapter). Later evidence-freshness binding:
        <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}history/pr/954`}>maka:pr:954</a>.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="schema"
    label="§05 · Schema"
    title="Make Self-check a finite object first"
    lede="Schema solves persistence and prompt safety; it does not alone prove evidence authenticity."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 2 · Model reports · Runtime admits · official truth lives elsewhere."
      alt="Three columns: Model advisory, Runtime gates, Authority elsewhere."
    >
      <AuthoritySplitFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <p>
      <code>self_check_submit</code> is not free text: status is only
      <code>pass / fail / inconclusive</code>; publicReason is bounded; at least one command or
      artifact evidence item; character/count caps on fields. Today many fields are model-submitted
      tool args — schema blocks unbounded payloads but cannot alone prove a command truly ran or a
      hash truly matches current bytes (Target: upgrade toward executor-owned, high-water-bound
      evidence).
    </p>
    <div class="stub">
      <p class="stub__tag">Current vs Target</p>
      <p>
        Current: Heavy-task Self-check is a strictly limited advisory mechanism, not an independent
        proof of task correctness. Target: promote declarations to executor-owned evidence — do not
        disguise as already shipped.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="authority"
    label="§05 · Authority"
    title="Chain authority back to facts"
    lede="Completion must not listen only to self-narration; official conclusions live in logs, external acceptance, and terminal facts."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 3 · Gate fails → check repair budget → bounded Repair Turn → re-check; stop when the cap is exhausted."
      alt="Five steps: Gate fails, Budget check, Repair Turn, Re-check, Stop loop."
    >
      <RepairBudgetFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <p>
      Building on §02: evidence must not be pruned away, nor overwritten by a self-narration. Building
      on §04: Self-check happens inside Attempt / Task loops under a repair budget. “Tests passed”
      from the model is still a report over public materials; Source Guard rejects private materials
      from feedback; when gates fail and budget is exhausted the self-check loop stops — it never
      grants infinite self-authority.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <div slot="outline">
    <ul class="outline-list">
      <li>Present: keystone + authority split + repair budget flow</li>
      <li>
        Aside: <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}history/pr/774`}>maka:pr:774</a>
      </li>
      <li>Still open: a11y pass — do not mark checklist complete</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</ChapterShell>

